- Contract addresses and network config from environment variables — never hardcode in components
- No mocked verification results presented as real on-chain results

## THE SOROBAN MENTAL MODEL
- Contracts compile to WASM and run in Soroban's deterministic VM
- NO standard library: #![no_std] on all contracts — cannot use std::
- ALL state is key-value storage in one of THREE tiers (Persistent/Temporary/Instance)
- NO implicit sender: env.require_auth(&address) is mandatory for every auth check
- WASM size limit: 64KB (post-Protocol 22) — optimize aggressively
- Resources are metered: CPU instructions, memory, ledger reads/writes, events — all cost fees

## STORAGE RULES — NON-NEGOTIABLE
1. Use Persistent storage for: token balances, user state, allowances, config
2. Use Temporary storage for: nonces, rate limits, expiring locks — NEVER critical state
3. Use Instance storage for: admin address, metadata, simple flags
   NEVER put growing/unbounded data in Instance — it loads on EVERY call
4. ALWAYS extend TTL on read/write of Persistent data:
   env.storage().persistent().extend_ttl(&key, LEDGER_THRESHOLD, LEDGER_BUMP)
   Where LEDGER_THRESHOLD ≈ 30 days and LEDGER_BUMP ≈ 31 days in ledgers
5. NEVER rely on Temporary data surviving between calls for security

## AUTHORIZATION RULES
- require_auth is the ONLY auth mechanism — there is NO implicit msg.sender
- Call from.require_auth() in transfer() — no exceptions
- Call admin.require_auth() in privileged operations
- For sub-contract calls: auth propagates only if explicitly passed
- Never skip require_auth because "the function seems safe" — it is not

## RUST CONTRACT RULES
- #![no_std] on every contract file — required for WASM target
- Use soroban_sdk::{contract, contractimpl, Env, Address, Symbol, Map, Vec}
- NO std::collections — use soroban_sdk::Map, Vec, String
- Error handling: use #[contracterror] enum with explicit integer discriminants
- Arithmetic: Soroban uses i128 for amounts — use .checked_add() / .checked_mul()
- Events: env.events().publish((contract_id, symbol), data) for all state changes
- #[contracttype] for all custom data structures stored on-chain
- Keep functions small and single-purpose — WASM binary size counts
- Use OpenZeppelin Stellar Contracts for token standards (audited)

## TESTING RULES
- soroban-sdk provides RegisteredContract test framework — use it
- Tests live in tests/ or as mod tests inside contract file
- Use Env::default() for unit tests (no network needed)
- Test every function: happy path + all error variants
- Test TTL extension logic: verify data survives expected TTL window
- Test auth: call functions without require_auth and assert the error

## SECURITY RULES
- require_auth missing = critical vulnerability (most common Soroban exploit)
- Unbounded Instance storage = DoS vulnerability
- Temporary storage for critical state = data loss vulnerability
- Never store secrets or private keys in contract storage — storage is public
- Validate all inputs: check zero amounts, check address != zero, array bounds
- For upgradeable contracts: protect update_current_contract_wasm with admin auth
- Emitting events for all state changes is mandatory — not optional

## FRONTEND / SDK RULES
- Use @stellar/stellar-sdk (JavaScript/TypeScript)
- Simulate before submitting: server.simulateTransaction() for fee estimation + error preview
- Use Stellar Wallets Kit for browser wallet integration in this project
- Use Launchtube for managed tx submission (handles fees + sequence numbers)
- For passkey/smart wallet: use passkey-kit SDK
